A non-governmental organisation (NGO) in the FCT, elpline Foundation for the Needy, has called on Nigerians not to stigmatise patients with tuberculosis, noting that the disease has remained the leading cause of morbidity and mortality in developing countries. President/founder of the NGO, Dr. Jumai Ahmadu, who made the call during a press briefing in Abuja, also tasked relevant authorities to step up efforts to end the global TB epidemic, even as she advocated for early diagnosis, treatment and palliative care. Ahmadu, noted that TB remains the world’s deadliest infectious killer, adding that each day, over 4,000 people lose their lives to TB, while close to 30,000 people fall ill with this preventable and curable disease. She pointed out that TB accounts for 7 per cent of all deaths in developing countries, which, according to her, is the most common cause of death from a single source of infection among adults, with children constituting 10 per cent of the new cases. Speaking on the 2020 theme: “It’s time”, Ahmadu described the theme as apt, stressing that the battle against TB require collective responsibility of both government and personal commitment. She continued: “Each year, we commemorate World Tuberculosis (TB) Day on March 24 to raise public awareness about the devastating health, social and economic consequences of TB, and to step up efforts to end the global TB epidemic. “In this race to combat a disease that knows no boundaries, it is necessary to have a conceptual and clear understanding of TB overall with the hope of providing better treatment through novel and collaborative research and public health efforts. “World TB Day aims to save millions of preventable deaths each year by raising awareness about TB, and pushing governments and individuals across the globe to take action against the disease as in the case with the COVID-19. “